description:
File: lichen/subsys/lichen/transport/slip_transport.c
Lines: 259-276

When an invalid escape sequence is received (ESC followed by anything other than ESC_END or ESC_ESC), the code logs a warning and increments slip_frame_errors, but then falls through to store the invalid byte:

    case SLIP_STATE_ESC:
        if (b == SLIP_ESC_END) {
            b = SLIP_END;
        } else if (b == SLIP_ESC_ESC) {
            b = SLIP_ESC;
        } else {
            /* Invalid escape sequence - treat as regular byte */
            LOG_WRN("SLIP RX: invalid escape sequence 0x%02x", b);
            ctx->stats.slip_frame_errors++;
        }
        ctx->rx_state = SLIP_STATE_DATA;
        if (ctx->rx_len < sizeof(ctx->rx_pkt)) {
            ctx->rx_pkt[ctx->rx_len++] = b;  // Stores corrupted byte!
        }

Per RFC 1055 and common implementations, invalid escape sequences should discard the entire frame, not silently corrupt it. Storing a corrupt byte violates protocol spec and could cause subtle data corruption.

Fix: Reset rx_state to IDLE, rx_len to 0, and return 0 (discard frame) on invalid escape.
